eas and information in authoritarian contexts through presentation of papers and panel sessions three key themes will be explored how individuals in authoritarian countries are using liberation technologies particularly the internet and mobile phones to expand pluralism and freedom how authoritarian states are censoring constraining monitoring and punishing the use of ict for that purpose how citizens and groups can circumvent authoritarian censorship and control of these technologies discussion will focus on these challenges generally and also specific developments in countries such as china iran cuba burma and north korea as well as russia and selected arab authoritarian regimes the conference is sponsored by the program on liberation technology at the center on democracy development and the rule of law at stanford in cooperation with the hoover institution downloads doc+ final agenda modified december 2010 microsoft word lib_tech__finalagenda doc 2.4 mb pdf+ participants bios modified december 2010 pdf liberation_technology_conferen pdf 195.1 kb pdf+ mackinnon rebecca networked authoritarianism in china and beyond implications for global internet freedom modified december 2010 pdf mackinnon_libtech pdf 256.9 kb pdf+ nicole wong's dinner speech modified january 2011 pdf 2010 10_nicole_wong_stanford_l pdf 237.7 kb location bechtel conference center encina hall 616 serra street stanford university stanford ca 94305 directions map fsi contact kathleen barcos parent research projects program on liberation technology program cddrl conferences series topics democracy liberation technology rule of law and corruption china cuba iran north korea russia search cddrl search within everything courses events fellowships news op eds people publications research other pages event news can information technology transform authoritarian regimes december 16 2010 program on liberation technology in the news events of interest the impact of technology access on protest frequency in a